WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:04.280
So our next speaker will be Rodrigo Silva Ferreira.

00:00:04.280 --> 00:00:07.600
Rodrigo is a QA engineer at Quoset,

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:10.280
where he contributes to the quality and usability

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:12.840
of open-source tools that empower data scientists

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:14.240
in R and Python.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:18.760
He focuses on both manual and automated testing strategies

00:00:18.760 --> 00:00:21.120
to ensure reliability, performance,

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:23.639
and an excellent user experience.

00:00:23.639 --> 00:00:26.000
All right, and without further ado,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:27.400
the floor is yours, Rodrigo.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:32.439
Yep, and, Rodrigo.

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:49.400
So, let's get started.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:52.200
Hi, everyone, and good afternoon.

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:54.639
Today I'll be presenting about

00:00:54.639 --> 00:00:56.759
The Notebook or Not to Notebook,

00:00:56.759 --> 00:00:59.959
Multilingual Workflows for Data Analysis.

00:01:00.279 --> 00:01:02.400
for Explorer for Data Analysis.

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:06.120
It's my first time in Canada, by the way,

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:09.800
and I'm really enjoying the experience so far.

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:10.919
So, I'm just gonna...

00:01:12.559 --> 00:01:15.839
So, thank you everyone from the organization,

00:01:15.839 --> 00:01:19.639
all the sponsors for organizing this amazing event.

00:01:19.639 --> 00:01:21.480
And without further ado,

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:24.680
I'll start by introducing myself a little bit.

00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:26.879
So, I'm originally from Brazil,

00:01:26.879 --> 00:01:28.480
from a city called Salvador.

00:01:28.519 --> 00:01:30.199
That's a picture of my city.

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:32.720
I'm based in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania,

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:34.800
and I work as a geoengineer at Posit.

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:38.160
And my background is in chemistry,

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:41.160
but the past few years I've been getting more

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:43.480
into statistics, data,

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:47.839
especially in the context of data analysis

00:01:47.839 --> 00:01:49.720
for issues of societal importance.

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:52.360
That's what I'm really interested in

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:54.559
because I believe that data and statistics

00:01:54.559 --> 00:01:57.760
can be really helpful in helping understand

00:01:57.760 --> 00:01:58.959
and improving the world.

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:02.480
And that's my personal blog,

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:04.080
in case anyone is interested.

00:02:05.239 --> 00:02:07.959
And yeah, so,

00:02:07.959 --> 00:02:09.080
what I'm really,

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:12.479
when I'm talking about something that I'm new to,

00:02:12.479 --> 00:02:16.039
I really like to stand on the shoulders of the ground.

00:02:16.039 --> 00:02:18.520
That's what people refer to that in academia.

00:02:19.559 --> 00:02:23.320
And I see a lot of this conference as a conversation

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:26.000
between different talks that happened

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:27.320
in different locations,

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:28.880
and then after the conference,

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:31.240
they all become available on YouTube.

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:33.160
And that's what I really find exciting,

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:34.559
to watch them later,

00:02:34.559 --> 00:02:36.960
and to see how they are interconnected,

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:39.639
and how the speakers have established

00:02:39.639 --> 00:02:43.399
that those conferences are meeting for dialogue,

00:02:43.399 --> 00:02:45.679
and for debates, and for conversations.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:49.080
And so with that in mind,

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:51.399
one of my favorite keynote talks

00:02:51.399 --> 00:02:55.080
that I attended recently was at Pi Data Boston,

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:57.919
which was given by one of my colleagues, actually,

00:02:57.919 --> 00:02:59.880
Isabel Zimmerman,

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:04.199
and she talked about the importance of tools,

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:06.080
why we should care about tools,

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:09.600
about using them, and about using them.

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:11.919
And that talk really struck with me,

00:03:11.919 --> 00:03:15.520
because that made me even more interested

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:19.119
in the tools that we use for data science,

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:21.119
but more in general,

00:03:21.119 --> 00:03:24.679
the tools that we use every day, for example.

00:03:25.279 --> 00:03:27.479
So some of the questions I had,

00:03:27.479 --> 00:03:29.759
after Isabel's keynote,

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:33.520
were more general in terms of human history,

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:36.919
like what was the first tool that was ever made?

00:03:36.919 --> 00:03:38.240
Who created it?

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:40.440
Where, when, and how?

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:42.479
And I think thinking about those questions

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:44.600
can really guide us,

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:47.919
as we think about tools that we use for programming,

00:03:47.919 --> 00:03:50.080
for data analysis, and so on.

00:03:50.119 --> 00:03:53.440
So that's why I find it very interesting

00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:58.720
to think beyond just the technical aspects of what we do,

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:01.080
but to also think in terms of

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:04.960
the importance of these things for us as humans.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:08.639
So trying to look for an answer for these questions,

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:11.360
I found out that the first tool ever made

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:13.360
were stones, essentially,

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:15.520
and the first stones that were found

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:18.480
were 3.4 million years ago,

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:20.760
which, it was very shocking to me,

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:23.640
because us, modern humans,

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:26.959
has only been around for 300,000 years.

00:04:26.959 --> 00:04:31.000
So it's been, essentially, a very, very long time ago.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.160
And what I found very interesting about this

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:37.880
is that shows that us, as humans,

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:40.559
we are always trying to create,

00:04:40.559 --> 00:04:43.320
and innovate, and use tools across time.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:48.040
And, but what do these ancient stones

00:04:48.040 --> 00:04:50.640
have to do with multilingual notebooks?

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:52.880
Why am I bringing it up?

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:56.160
So the reason I'm bringing it up is because, again,

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:00.440
to reflect how these tools inform what we do,

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:04.160
and how we use them to achieve certain goals.

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:07.600
So I really encourage everyone to check the talk

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:11.239
by PyData Boston, that's available on YouTube.

00:05:11.239 --> 00:05:13.000
And without further ado,

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.200
let's talk about the basic anatomy of a Jupyter Notebook,

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:21.079
which is one of the tools that we will be exploring today.

00:05:21.079 --> 00:05:26.079
So this is from a talk on the history of Jupyter Notebooks,

00:05:27.119 --> 00:05:28.480
that was presented.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:32.279
How many of you here are familiar with Jupyter Notebooks?

00:05:32.279 --> 00:05:33.959
Yeah, everyone.

00:05:33.959 --> 00:05:34.799
Cool.

00:05:34.799 --> 00:05:37.359
So everyone knows how it looks like.

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:41.000
And what I find very interesting about Jupyter Notebooks,

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:46.679
is the development of more and more extensions around it,

00:05:48.359 --> 00:05:50.880
that are contributed by the community.

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:54.839
So everyone knows how to prep the docs

00:05:54.839 --> 00:05:58.239
for the different extensions, and so on.

00:05:58.239 --> 00:06:01.920
And these extensions allow for users

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:05.799
to extend the capabilities of Jupyter Notebooks.

00:06:05.799 --> 00:06:09.079
One extension that I find really exciting, for example,

00:06:09.079 --> 00:06:12.160
is to translate between different languages,

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:16.000
human languages, that's what I'm referring to here.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.279
That allows it to translate the Markdown cells,

00:06:19.279 --> 00:06:21.359
what you have written on a notebook,

00:06:21.359 --> 00:06:22.959
into different languages.

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:26.880
So in terms of the current state

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:30.559
of the Jupyter extension ecosystem,

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:34.920
one website that I found out recently,

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:38.359
is the Jupyter Extension Marketplace.

00:06:38.359 --> 00:06:41.920
And that website allows us to explore

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:44.959
different types of extensions that are available,

00:06:44.959 --> 00:06:48.880
as well as extending some telemetry data

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:50.239
about each of the extensions.

00:06:50.239 --> 00:06:54.519
So we can see how many downloads have been made

00:06:54.519 --> 00:06:57.160
in the past month, in the past year,

00:06:57.160 --> 00:06:58.559
for each of the extensions,

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:02.799
which extensions are the most popular, and so on.

00:07:02.799 --> 00:07:06.239
So I find that that website

00:07:06.239 --> 00:07:08.440
is not maintained by Project Jupyter,

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:10.519
it's an unofficial website,

00:07:10.519 --> 00:07:14.000
but I find that really informative

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.760
when I'm looking for extensions

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:20.640
that fit into a particular purpose, and so on.

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:23.480
So there are some examples of extensions

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:26.720
for different purposes.

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:29.559
One of them is they're really like your API widgets,

00:07:29.559 --> 00:07:34.559
which enable widget interactivity in a notebook, and so on.

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:37.839
So in the context of this talk,

00:07:37.839 --> 00:07:40.559
in which we're talking about multilingual workflows,

00:07:41.799 --> 00:07:45.480
some extensions can be really helpful

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:49.880
when you want to run different languages within a notebook.

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:53.399
And those are under that category

00:07:53.399 --> 00:07:56.320
of runtime and kernel extensions.

00:07:57.239 --> 00:07:59.160
And the reason I really like them

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:02.239
is because they can enable multilingual execution,

00:08:02.279 --> 00:08:05.279
so you can have R execution within a notebook,

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:07.480
Python, SQL, and so on.

00:08:10.239 --> 00:08:12.239
And when I was at PyDatabase,

00:08:12.239 --> 00:08:15.119
I did a live stream with Ian DeBrieve,

00:08:15.119 --> 00:08:16.679
who works for Matlab,

00:08:16.679 --> 00:08:21.359
and he was essentially showing how he can run

00:08:21.359 --> 00:08:25.160
a Matlab engine within a Jupyter notebook.

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:30.160
And that's one example of how multilingual kernel extensions

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:34.000
can be helpful for data analysis.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And by the way, those circles that I put out of the way

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:42.440
are for a playlist with all the videos

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:44.119
that I mentioned throughout the talk.

00:08:44.119 --> 00:08:48.080
So in case you're interested of checking different talks

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:49.280
from other conference later

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:52.239
that are related to what I'm talking about,

00:08:52.239 --> 00:08:53.679
that can be really helpful.

00:08:55.880 --> 00:08:59.280
So a lot of what I'm exploring here

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:01.599
as the basis for this talk

00:09:01.599 --> 00:09:04.760
in terms of the history of Jupyter notebooks

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:09.760
came from this previous talk at EuroPython,

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:11.359
which I found very interesting

00:09:11.359 --> 00:09:14.239
because it gives a very solid overview

00:09:14.239 --> 00:09:17.679
of the history of Jupyter notebooks.

00:09:17.679 --> 00:09:20.320
And what I found very exciting about them

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:23.119
is that it has had a lot of progress

00:09:23.119 --> 00:09:26.440
in the past 25 years, I would say,

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:30.679
with IPython being created in 2001,

00:09:30.679 --> 00:09:35.520
and then IPython notebook first being released 2011.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.479
And then the project Jupyter

00:09:37.479 --> 00:09:41.840
being spun off from IPython in 2014.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:44.039
And then there was the first JupyterCon

00:09:44.039 --> 00:09:46.239
almost 10 years ago, like nine years ago.

00:09:47.159 --> 00:09:50.520
And then the stable release of JupyterLab.

00:09:50.520 --> 00:09:55.520
And by 2018, there were 2.7 million notebooks on GitHub.

00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:59.119
And a few years ago, about five years ago,

00:09:59.119 --> 00:10:03.479
Nature named Jupyter as one of the 10 projects

00:10:03.479 --> 00:10:05.280
that confirmed science,

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:08.320
and it reached almost 10 million notebooks on GitHub.

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:12.640
So this very exciting history

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:14.640
in the rise of Jupyter notebooks

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.400
is not without controversies, though,

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:22.520
because some people really like notebooks

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:25.440
and some people really dislike notebooks.

00:10:26.239 --> 00:10:27.799
So I don't know if you're familiar

00:10:27.799 --> 00:10:31.760
with these two talks that were given before.

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:35.919
The first one is I Don't Like Notebooks,

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:38.320
which was given at JupyterCon.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:45.200
And the second one is a PyData talk

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:50.880
that was given at one of those PyData conferences

00:10:51.039 --> 00:10:53.080
called The First Notebook War.

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:55.200
And then there were these very interesting blog posts

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:56.799
that came up as well,

00:10:56.799 --> 00:10:58.799
someone talked about contextualizing

00:10:58.799 --> 00:11:01.159
that first notebook war,

00:11:01.159 --> 00:11:04.640
and someone else responding to the I Don't Like Notebooks

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:07.559
talk, talking about how they like notebooks.

00:11:08.479 --> 00:11:12.640
So there's a lot of controversy around notebooks.

00:11:13.559 --> 00:11:18.559
And the reason why I love notebooks

00:11:18.599 --> 00:11:22.679
beyond or despite of the technical aspects

00:11:22.679 --> 00:11:26.280
is because, first, the idea of memory

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:29.679
and reproducibility in data science,

00:11:29.679 --> 00:11:33.159
as notebooks can remember the computation state,

00:11:33.159 --> 00:11:35.599
and you can pick up where you left

00:11:35.599 --> 00:11:38.760
and continue your reproducible workflow.

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.359
Second, the idea of collaboration and community.

00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:47.719
Third, narratives and incremental thinking,

00:11:47.719 --> 00:11:51.599
how you can develop your analysis step by step,

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:53.760
making it easy to share with people

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:55.640
through codes, visualizations,

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:57.520
and explanations along the way.

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:03.640
Fourth, the bridge between computational and storytelling,

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:06.479
because you can tell your story with the data

00:12:06.479 --> 00:12:09.760
in a way that can be engaging to your audience.

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:14.760
And besides all these reasons

00:12:15.679 --> 00:12:18.479
that go beyond the technical aspects,

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:24.359
as I was reflecting about PyCon US last year,

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:29.080
I think there is one more reason that cannot be ignored,

00:12:29.080 --> 00:12:32.440
which is just the act of playing

00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:36.520
in the playful nature of exploratory data analogies.

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:39.880
And the reason why I say that I was reflecting about this

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:41.679
based on PyCon US last year,

00:12:41.679 --> 00:12:45.039
because there was this very cool keynote talk

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:46.799
from Lynn Root,

00:12:46.799 --> 00:12:49.320
in which she talks about the importance

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:52.200
of just playing in general.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:55.679
So in this, like nowadays we have this pressure

00:12:55.679 --> 00:13:00.200
to always be doing things for a particular purpose,

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:05.200
and because of work, or demands, or different goals,

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:08.159
I think it's really important as well

00:13:08.159 --> 00:13:11.880
to think about the idea of data exploration

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:14.239
just out of curiosity,

00:13:14.239 --> 00:13:18.159
and out of the desire to better understand the world.

00:13:18.159 --> 00:13:19.960
So that's what I find really exciting

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:24.159
about exploratory data analysis

00:13:24.159 --> 00:13:26.479
with notebooks in particular.

00:13:30.799 --> 00:13:33.799
So yeah, so besides being playful,

00:13:33.799 --> 00:13:37.440
I've come to realize that data scientists are multilingual.

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:43.400
Here's some data from the Kaggle survey from 2022,

00:13:44.039 --> 00:13:47.280
which shows that Python, SQL, and R

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:51.719
are the third most used languages among data scientists.

00:13:53.239 --> 00:13:57.679
And then there's your full data from 2018 to 2022.

00:13:57.679 --> 00:14:01.039
2022 was the last year that they conducted that survey.

00:14:03.039 --> 00:14:07.320
And here we can see that there has been a rise in usage

00:14:08.200 --> 00:14:10.320
among data scientists of Python,

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:14.520
and SQL is increasing, and R, although it's decreasing,

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:16.000
it seems to be stable.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.239
Like there's a very strong community

00:14:19.239 --> 00:14:20.840
that remains using R,

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:24.640
especially for statistical analysis purposes and so on.

00:14:27.039 --> 00:14:32.039
So as I see those different trends in Python,

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:34.280
SQL, and R adoption,

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:35.919
they really make me wonder

00:14:35.919 --> 00:14:39.400
about what they mean for notebooks.

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:41.880
For me, it means that this data science

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:44.520
is increasingly polyglot.

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:47.799
It means that notebooks and IDEs should be true,

00:14:49.359 --> 00:14:52.479
as real-world projects in their communities

00:14:52.479 --> 00:14:54.320
often use multiple languages.

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:59.320
So you can have a data scientist who prefers to use SQL

00:14:59.799 --> 00:15:02.239
because they are more into data engineering,

00:15:02.239 --> 00:15:05.840
or a statistician who prefers to use R and so on,

00:15:07.919 --> 00:15:10.000
as each of those languages are often used

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.599
for different purposes.

00:15:12.599 --> 00:15:14.960
So it's the same idea of tools

00:15:15.880 --> 00:15:19.320
and how people choose to use the tools that they need

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:23.599
and they prefer in order to see a particular need

00:15:23.599 --> 00:15:24.760
and purpose.

00:15:25.599 --> 00:15:30.599
So, in terms of multilingual notebook workflows,

00:15:32.119 --> 00:15:35.280
I want to show an example of how to integrate

00:15:37.159 --> 00:15:38.960
multiple languages within a notebook.

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:43.359
So a classic example would be using SQL

00:15:43.359 --> 00:15:45.359
to extract data from a database,

00:15:45.359 --> 00:15:47.440
Python to obtain and to affirm data,

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:51.640
and R with a stronger focus on statistics.

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:53.239
And there are two approaches

00:15:53.359 --> 00:15:55.320
of tackling such workflows.

00:15:55.320 --> 00:15:58.559
One of them is using notebooks.

00:15:58.559 --> 00:16:02.280
As you know, there is also Quarto,

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:04.440
which I just used before,

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:09.039
which has a similar idea, but different concept,

